Rating: 4
I make this every year for Christmas gift giving (I make a bunch of different scones, wrap two of each in plastic wrap and foil and tuck them into a bag with jelly/jam, tea, and the recipes - ALWAYS a big hit!) Everyone LOVES these and they freeze incredibly well. I shape it into a large circle, cut it into wedges with a pizza cutter and bake on a baking stone. Perfect, and an absoltely HEAVENLY smell!

Rating: 3
These are very tasty--just keep an eye on them so they don't dry out. I like to make 2 circles and cut each into 6 wedges. My husband, who isn't a fan of scones loves these!

Rating: 3
My spices for this recipe - 1 heaping tsp. cinnamon, 1 heaping tsp. ginger, 1/2 tsp. ground cloves. As I only had 1/3 cup golden raisins, I added 1/3 cup currants, which really came out well. Also took the advice of one reviewer and brushed tops with water and sprinkled with cinnamon-sugar prior to cutting and baking. Awesome, awesome scone recipe. It will be a great holiday addition to my snack table.

Rating: 3
I added extra spice and left out the raisins, but next time I will double the spice. The dough is beautiful; soft, but not sticky. Another way to make these is to divide the dough into halves until you have eight pieces, then shape them into balls. Instead of brushing with milk, then sprinkling with sugar, I just pressed the tops in a small bowl of sugar. When the scones bake, the tops get all cracked and crinkled like a ginger snap! Very pretty. Lemon curd and whipped cream goes very well with this.

Rating: 2
These smelled great in the making and baking process...I'd give it a 2+, they were very good but the gingerbread taste was much lighter than I would like. I left out the raisins, and would make it again- hiking up the spice levels.

Rating: 3
Currently my favorite scone recipe! Dark, soft, and delicious, especially with a glass of milk. I brushed the top with water and sprinkled it with sugar, which added an extra sparkle. Yum!